{"key":"post-8529367","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8529367</id>\n<content>To answer your direct question, fruiting started early because you were fanning out the air around the substrate.&amp;nbsp; Air exchange is the number one pinning trigger, and you're not supposed to fan until after full colonization.&amp;nbsp;  During colonization, you're only supposed to provide a means of gas exchange, which keeps CO2 levels high, delaying pinning until the proper time, at which you begin fanning.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Perlite is for humidity, not for use as a moisture reservior.&amp;nbsp; Next time, don't use a layer of perlite under the substrate.&amp;nbsp; Plain verm is also one of the worst possible casing materials.&amp;nbsp; It's used on pf cakes for simplicity, but when you moved to cased substrates, I'd suggest a pasteurized peat based casing layer.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8529380</next>\n<prev>8529364</prev>\n<first>8529054</first>\n<last>10022039</last>\n<when>1213632622</when>\n<utime>06/16/08 07:10 PM</utime>\n</post>"}